    {
      "type": "text",
      "title": "Suggested Triage Order",
      "text": "A strong minimal triage flow on Linux is:\n\n1. file target\n2. sha256sum target\n3. strings -a target | less\n4. readelf -h/-S/-s target\n5. objdump -Mintel -d target | less\n6. ldd target\n7. strace -f ./target\n\nThat sequence usually tells you what the binary is, what it depends on, what text clues it contains, and what it does at runtime."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "title": "EXAMPLE: FAST ELF TRIAGE",
      "language": "bash",
      "code": "file ./target\nsha256sum ./target\nstrings -a ./target | less\nreadelf -h ./target\nreadelf -S ./target\nreadelf -s ./target | less\nldd ./target"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "title": "EXAMPLE: RUNTIME OBSERVATION",
      "language": "bash",
      "code": "strace -f -o trace.txt ./target arg1 arg2\ngrep -E 'open|read|write|connect|execve' trace.txt\ncat /proc/$(pgrep target)/maps"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "title": "EXAMPLE: PATCH A FEW BYTES",
      "language": "bash",
      "code": "cp target target.bak\nprintf '\\x90\\x90' | dd of=target bs=1 seek=$((0x1234)) conv=notrunc"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "title": "EXAMPLE: EXTRACT A REGION",
      "language": "bash",
      "code": "dd if=target of=chunk.bin bs=1 skip=$((0x400)) count=$((0x100))"
    }
  ]
}